In Salt Lake City, officials closed all theaters.
George Rinhart/Corbis via Getty ImagesThe 1918 flu is not a perfect comparison point for COVID-19.
For instance: To the chagrin of those suffering Salt Lake City actors, not all cities closed their theaters.
But like today, one defining fact of quarantine life was the patchwork of local laws under which people lived.
Maybe no fact of quarantine in 1918 resonates as much today as the awkward position it left the education system in.